'''Kathleen Lyttelton''' (born '''Mary Kathleen Clive'''), 1856{{snd}}12 January 1907, was a women's activist, editor and writer. She devoted much of her life to fighting for women's suffrage and for the improvement of women's lives in general.<ref name="DNB"/> After a period of 11 years in Cambridge, as wife of [[Selwyn College, Cambridge|Selwyn College]]'s first Master [[Arthur Lyttelton]], she concentrated on her writing and women's committee work. In her 1901 book ''Women and Their Work'' she argued that education for women was "essential to their true progress", with the franchise being a necessary part of that education. 

==Early life==

Kathleen was born in 1856. Her father was the judge and Liberal politician [[George Clive (Liberal politician)|George Clive]], her mother Ann Sybella Martha Farquhar.<ref name="DNB">{{Cite book |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/50712 |title=Lyttelton [née Clive], Mary Kathleen (1856–1907), women's activist |work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |access-date=27 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="peerage"/>

In spite of the initial misgivings of her father, in 1880 she married the Hon [[Arthur Lyttelton]],{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}} then a tutor at [[Keble College, Oxford]].<ref name="TimesObit">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/archive/article/1907-01-15/9/7.html#start%3D1906-12-01%26end%3D1908-09-29%26terms%3Darthur%20lyttelton%26back%3D/tto/archive/find/arthur+lyttelton/w:1906-12-01%7E1908-09-29/o:date/1%26prev%3D/tto/archive/frame/goto/arthur+lyttelton/w:1906-12-01%7E1908-09-29/o:date/9%26next%3D/tto/archive/frame/goto/arthur+lyttelton/w:1906-12-01%7E1908-09-29/o:date/11 |title=Obituary |date=15 January 1907 |work=The Times |access-date=27 November 2018 |page=9}}</ref> Fortunately the marriage proved strong and the couple went on to have three children: Margaret Lucy (1882){{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}}, Archer Geoffrey (1884){{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}}, and Stephen Clive (1887){{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}}.<ref name="peerage">{{cite book |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p1436.htm#i14351 |editor1-last=Mosley |editor1-first=Charles |title=Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage |edition=107th |volume=1 |location=[[Wilmington, Delaware]] |publisher=Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd |year=2003 |page=839}}</ref>
==Cambridge==

In 1882 Kathleen and Arthur took up residence in the newly-founded [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]], where Arthur had been appointed Master-designate. When they moved in, the college was still a building site with only the West front completed. Initially, they made do with a suite of adapted student rooms until the Master's Lodge was built.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}}

Kathleen founded The Cambridge Association For Women's Suffrage (CAWS) along with [[Millicent Fawcett]] in 1884,{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}} and Fawcett encouraged her to join the Executive of The Central Society For Women’s Suffrage.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}. She was also active with the Cambridge Women's Refuge, helping to raise funds for what would become the Cambridge Association for the Care of Girls which aimed to help girls of the streets and to give them practical help with domestic economy and literacy.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

In 1890, with her close friend [[Louise Creighton]], Kathleen founded the Cambridge Ladies Dining Society, a group of believers in women's education who actively campaigned for the University to grant degrees to women; most were also strong supporters of female suffrage. Members of the society included [[Caroline Jebb]], [[Eleanor Sidgwick]], [[Mary Augusta Ward]], and [[Mary Paley Marshall]].{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

During their years at Selwyn, the Lyttletons also helped develop the College Music Society, and they supported the Boat Club (whose colours were chosen by Kathleen).{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=60}}

==Lancashire==
In 1893 after 11 years in Cambridge, Arthur left Selwyn to take up the post of [[vicar]] of [[Eccles, Greater Manchester|Eccles]] Parish Church in [[Lancashire]]. In 1895, along with Arthur, she founded and later became chair of the executive committee of the Manchester and Salford Women's Trade Union Council, an organisation whose aim was to investigate working conditions and organise low-paid workers into unions. Members of the council included [[Christabel Pankhurst]] and [[CP Scott]].{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

She launched the Eccles branch of the [[Co-operative Women's Guild|Cooperative Women's Guild]], and became a vice president of the [[National Council of Women of Great Britain|National Union of Women Workers]], as well as joining the committee of the Manchester National Society for Women's Suffrage. As an active [[Board of guardians|Poor Law Guardian]], she complained that [[Manchester]] city officials "winked at the pollution of the atmosphere".{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

Kathleen's course of lectures for the Manchester School of Domestic Economy entitled ''Common Sense For Housewives: Girls’ Life after Leaving School'' was published by the school in 1896.<ref name="BLcat002297038"/>{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

==Hampshire==

After Arthur was appointed [[Suffragan bishop|Suffragan Bishop]] of [[Southampton]] in 1898 the family moved back south,{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}} to [[Petersfield|Petersfield, Hampsire]].

Kathleen was elected president of the National Union of Women's Workers, and she chaired their conference in [[Brighton]] in 1900.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

Kathleen's book ''Women and Their Work,''<ref name="BLcat002297040"/> published in 1901, was permeated with her deep religious beliefs.<ref name="DNB"/> In it, she insisted on the importance of education for women and the necessity of ‘commitment’ and ‘conviction’; she argued that while the difficult lives of working class women would naturally lead to the formation of definite opinions, the sheltered, easy lives of middle and upper-class women did not naturally lead to such ‘conviction’. She wrote that "the withholding of the franchise is very prejudicial to the right development of women, and that the education given by the vote is essential to their true progress",<ref name="DNB"/> foreseeing that “the bewilderment will pass as the years go on, and the very magnitude of the task will in time arise and awaken those women who are as yet indifferent to it".{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=61}}

Following Arthur's death in February 1903, Kathleen edited a collection of his essays entitled ''Modern Poets of Faith, Doubt and Paganism'' (1904).<ref name="BLcat002296898" />{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=62}}

In June 1903 she became editor of the women's section of an Anglican weekly publication called ''[[The Guardian (Anglican newspaper)|The Guardian]]'', in which role she was the first to review and publish the early writings of Virginia Stephen (later [[Virginia Woolf]]). Virginia was initially hesitant and grateful, but by late 1905 had become sufficiently confident to complain that Mrs L "sticks her broad thumb into the middle of my sentences and improves the moral tone".{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=62}}

==London==

Kathleen moved to a house in [[Gower Street, London|Gower Street]], London, near that of [[Millicent Fawcett]] with whom she published ''Why Women Want the Vote'' in 1906.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=62}}
==Death==

Kathleen died at the age of 51 on 12 January 1907, at the Clives’ family seat at at Perrystone Court, [[Herefordshire]].<ref name="TimesObit"/> Her obituary in [[The Times]]  made no mention of her suffrage and TUC work, and concentrated on her role as a scholarly translator, "a considerable student of literature" and a "diligent critic”.<ref name="TimesObit"/>{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=62}} There were also obituaries in ''The Englishwoman's Review''<ref name="EWR">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3vDiDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=%22Mrs+Arthur+Lyttelton%22&source=bl&ots=4ngLdnvd_s&sig=kxyo-Xok7zNMiRYrV35EHBEASv8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi3uoTYxPXeAhUpJ8AKHXk1BpM4ChDoATAEegQIBBAB#v=onepage&q=%22Mrs%20Arthur%20Lyttelton%22&f=false |title=Sorrowful News. The Death of Mrs. Arthur Lyttelton. |work=The Englishwoman's Review of Social and Industrial Questions: 1907-1908 |publisher=Routlage |editor-last=Murray |editor-first=Janet Horowitz |access-date=27 November 2018 |editor-last2=Stark |editor-first2=Myra}} [Reprinted articles]</ref> and ''[[The Guardian (Anglican newspaper)|The Guardian]]''.{{sfn|Chothia|2018|p=62}}

==Select publications==

* 1886: Translator of ''Nature and the Bible: Lectures on the Mosaic history of Creation in its relation to Natural Science'' by [[Franz Heinrich Reusch]] <ref name="BLcat003078632">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003078632&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=27 November 2018}}</ref>
