'''Peter Hallward''' is a [[Political philosophy|political philosopher]], best known for his work on [[Alain Badiou]] and [[Gilles Deleuze]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelondongraduateschool.co.uk/blog/listen-to-peter-hallward-re-educating-the-educator/|title=Listen to Peter Hallward, 'Re-educating the Educator' |publisher=London Graduate School|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref> He has also published works on [[post-colonialism]] and contemporary [[Haiti]]. Hallward is a member of the editorial collective of the journal ''[[Radical Philosophy]]'' and a contributing editor to ''[[Angelaki: Journal of the Theoretical Humanities]]''.

After completing his PhD at [[Yale University]] in French and [[African-American studies|African-American]] studies, Hallward became a lecturer, and then reader, of [[French philosophy]] and [[French literature|literature]] at [[King's College London]] from 1999 to 2004. He then joined the Centre for Research in Modern European Philosophy, which relocated from [[Middlesex University]] to [[Kingston University]]. He is now a professor of Modern European Philosophy at [[Kingston University]].<ref name=kingstonuni>{{Cite web|url=http://fass.kingston.ac.uk/faculty/staff/cv.php?staffnum=734|title=Prof Peter Hallward – Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences |publisher=Kingston University London|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref>

== Work ==
Hallward is currently working on a three part project on key philosophers of [[Will (philosophy)|political will]]: [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau|Rousseau]], [[Louis Auguste Blanqui|Blanqui]], and [[Karl Marx|Marx]]. He is simultaneously working on a larger book entitled 'The Will of the People,' which will "develop and defend a notion of democratic political will, understood as a rational, deliberate, and autonomous capacity for collective self-determination."<ref name=kingstonuni/>

